ce:section.ce:para:
NTO is an appropriate material for photocatalysis owing to its multiple band levels, and superior for light absorption. Demonstrations have shown their applications in photocatalytic WOR and other photoredox catalysis [31–33]. In this study, NTO is synthesized according to a modified Pechini method [34], and the CQDs loaded on NTO by impregnation-sintering approach. The structures and morphologies of the samples are studied by scanning electronic microscopy (SEM) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM). Homogenous NTO nanoparticles can be received by this synthesis as shown from SEM and TEM images in Fig. 1

                     a and 1b, respectively. The diameter of the NTO particles is presented in the inset of Fig. 1a, and it ranges between 30 and 60 nm with the dominant diameter ca. 50 nm. In addition, the CQDs loaded NTO samples are also studied by SEM (
                        Figure S1
                     ), but too small to observe. The surface area of NTO powder is investigated by BET (
                        Figure S2
                     ), namely 28.2 m2/g with a mean of pore width ca. 18 nm, and the results are close to the results after loading CQDs.

To clarify the role of CQDs in this WOR, we have acquired both thermodynamic and kinetic studies. Ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) is used to study the thermodynamic properties of the samples (
                        Figure S17
                     ). The long Fermi tail of NTO leads an extrapolation of 1.50 eV, which stands as the distance between the Fermi level and valence band. This value is preserved by loading CQDs, revealing an insignificantly affected on the potential of valence band maximum. We also acquire time-resolved PL to study the manners of the photoexcitation charges (

                        Figure S18
                     ), and insignificant effect can be realized for photoexcitation charge when NTO was loaded CQDs.
